Fusion 360 This was my first project using Fusion 360. I found Fusion 360 to work very well for this, and am getting more comfortable using the various options. I'd encourage others to give it a try as it's easy enough to do simple things, but powerful enough to accomplish the most complex designs. Add in that it's free for personal non-commercial use, and it's hard to beat. This is a battery box and cover for a Multistar 6sx5200mah 10C lipo. I developed this box for the Firefly6 but it could be used for just about anything using this lipo. Unfortunately the box will stick out above the wing of the Firefly6 (and flush with the bottom of the wing), so I developed farings to go around the top perimeter of the the box to create smoother airflow over it. If you use this for the Firefly6, you'll need to print two of each file. However, on the second print set, the box, and all the faring files will be needed to be mirrored about their longest dimensions to create a right and left hand set.
When installing this in the FF6, you'll need to cut the inside-most edge of the existing battery box such that the rear inside corner of the printed boxes touch the composite frame of the center fuse. The protusion for the power cable (on the box print) will be closer to the front of the wings. Also you'll need to cut the existing box through to the bottom of the wing (removing the installed magnets in the process). Go to the RCgroups thread for the Firefly6 and see my posts there using these printed parts for more info. You can search my posts in that thread to find them (billyd60 is my name on RCG).

description.header: LULZBOT TAZ LCD w/ Pi Enclosure
description.text:
This is a custom LCD mount for the Lulzbot Taz that includes a mounting location with wire holes for a Raspberry Pi to run Octoprint (webpage based print server). The goals of the LCD were this:
  • Allow a Pi to be mounted with the LCD (and get Pi off my desk)
  • Use the same mounting hardware as the original LCD enclosure
  • Provide easy access for wires in side of case
  • Keep volume to a reasonable size
    • NOTE: You will most likely need a left angle micro USB cable to power the Pi due to space limitations. These can be found pretty cheaply on Newegg and Amazon (or your country's equivalent mega store) You will also need 4x M2.5 6mm bolts from your local hardware store to mount the Pi The OpenSCAD source file is also attached to allow for easy modification and remixes. Have fun with it and throw me a remix hook so I can see your cool mod ideas.

Here are a list of things I would like to add in the future if I can get around to it:
  • Add a slot for the SD card. Don't need it with Octoprint but would be a nice option in scad
  • Add a mount on the back for a Raspberry Pi Camera angled to watch the bed

2) The Pi is installed with 4x M2.5 6mm bolts that I picked up from my local hardware store
3) The enclosure is used for frame support on the Taz so DO NOT move it between removing the old enclosure and installing the new one. It should be fine as the bracing is redundant with the top brace but I would hate to see anyone accidentally knock their printer out of square.

description.text:
I have two light switches in my house that are hard to reach because they are behind furniture. The light switches in my house are the flat "Decora" style, so I could not use @Bingbingaling's extender for the "toggle" style. So I designed a new thing that works for me. This is a single piece print that has 2 captive moving parts. There is 0.2 mm of gap so that the sliding parts will not escape the 45 degree walled slot which contains them. My printer has a 150mm square bed and this design will just fit within that square when angled 45 degrees. see it here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n_84355Am7U You'll need two 3/4" long flathead 6-32 screws to mount this. If you have a larger print bed you may want to remix this and extend the handle. If you mount a longer one upside down then you can use it for young kids to reach the switch. Here's the source OpenSCAD file:
https://github.com/danmarshall/openscad-decora-switch-extension You can get the source OpenSCAD for just the sliding bolt component on my GitHub: https://github.com/danmarshall/openscad-sliding-bolt

This is my Modification of Alpinedrones great 180 unibody.
I have customised this to suit RCX H1306-3200 motors with Little Bee 20A ESC's.
4045 bullnose props
I made a recess for the motor to sit in, this is 2mm thick and allows correct fitting of the screws, the triangular cutouts are to allow air flow for cooling and a rectangular hole for the motor wires to pass through without stress.
I have then brought them up and around and direct onto the ESC.
So far the assembly of this machine has been very nice, as you can see from the photos I put a 50mm length of 5mm heat shrink over the motor wires, this just makes it look neater from the under side, standard small cable ties to hold it all in place. I am working on the top plate as well, I am trying something a little different in that I am mounting a Nase32 Rev6 and the Rx module (stacked) to the underside of the top plate I am not sure how this will work out but half the fun of experimenting. (stay tuned, Christmas build soI will post soon) Please note this is a work in progress I will post more as the build progresses.

Flashforge Dreamer

Rafts:

No

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm

60%

Notes: I set this for 6 bottom layers, 4 top layers and 4 perimeter layers.
The reason for this is strength of the motor mounts, this meant there was no infill used at the motor mount, I prefer 4 perimeter lays for these projects as it makes the areas where screws go through the frame a lot more solid.
I used a black carbon fibre filled PLA.
The only place I found where support was necessary was in the new rectangular holes where the motor wires pass through, so support is used very sparingly.

Tidy Up I used a de-buring tool, 2mm drill and a counter sinking tool to clean up the motor mount holes and edges of the frame etc.
This makes the finished item much nicer to handle.
Cleanup and removal of the support material in the motor holes requires a little attention but not much of a problem.

title: Scalar - Bowden to Direct Drive Adaptator

description.text:
This part is an adapator to convert a Bowden system into a Direct drive one. It is designed to be screwed on top of a AllInOne hot end support block.
There are 2 versions depending on the X carriage size:
  • 1 for Scalar XL
  • 1 for Scalar M

2016.01.19: update direct drive extruder body to fit M4 screw heads instead of M4 nuts hex fittings.
2015.12.28 - update the models, add some special parts called "ptfe" with a 7mm inner hole for a 6mm ptfe tube to be inserted inside. Also add some markings on the sides about what model/printer size it's for.

• E3D adaptor model. It has a 7mm center hole so that we can fit a 6mm PTFE tube inside. Also the extruder body has been updated to also support this 7mm hole up to the Mk8 bolt location. The whole system requires a PTFE tube of about 55mm so that it can snap into the Bowden E3D hot end and be long enough to reach the MK8 drive gear.
  • 2015.12.28 - AllInOne model is working fine up to now after a full week end of testing.
    • So far so good with the tests.

• You need less retraction
  • You have more torque applied directly on the filament
  • Less or no strings are forming during movements
  • You can use lower print temperature. (200°C instead of 210°C for example)
  • The Extruder body has a built in Pneumatic bowden connector hole so that you can still use the PTFE tube and the spool holder from the previous bowden version of the printer. In this configuration the filament will be pulled from the ptfe tube instead of pushed inside.
  • Print settings are easier to handle, it's a nice solution for a first printing experience.
  • you can use more of your filament, and now recycle the 1meter left over from the previous bowden version due to the tube length.

• You loose some build height as the stepper motor is placed on top of the hotend wich is in direct axis with the top of the printer frame.
  • You limit the printer ability to have fast mouvements and high accelerations
  • with filament that breaks easily, it can be a nightmare if the filament is broken inside the extruder body.
This part is still an untested prototype, some adjustments might come in the coming days.

• 2015.12.26: Update of the E3D model. it has a 7mm center hole instead of just 4mm
  • 2015.12.26: Add extruder body with a center hole of 7mm.
  • 2015.12.22: Update models with small fixes. Also add a E3D adaptor for Scalar XL printer

description.text:
WARNING: IF YOU ATTEMPT TO DO ANYTHING WITH THESE FILES, AND SCREW SOMETHING UP, ITS YOUR OWN DAMN FAULT. EVEN IF YOU SOMEHOW MANAGE TO ENABLE THE LINE, IT IS 400V, IF SOMETHING GOES WRONG, YOU WILL BLOW UP LIKE IN THE FILM DISTRICT 9, DON'T SAY I DIDN'T WARN YOU.
NEITHER MYSELF OR THE THINGIVERSE CAN BE HELD RESPONSIBLE FOR YOUR IDIOCY.
I was offended when I heard that the cost of this plug was over $3000, so I said to hell with them and started developing my own. (I have since heard that the price can drop to about $2500 each if you buy 100)
Source of other dimensions are primarily here, but I also took my own measurements
http://www.dyden.co.jp/topics/data/pdf/evkyusoku17p.pdf (pg 4)
Files created with blender, exported STL files repaired with netfab studio basic.
The point of this is to enable experimentation, not commercial production. So naturally, this is not engineered to be water tight or have the durability to be driven-over by a car. Safety nazis need not enquire.
The community collaboration is here: http://www.mynissanleaf.com/viewtopic.php?f=44&t=13349
These 3d printed parts are meant to enable experimentation and development, not commercial production.
I envision a charger that is portable, isolated, and can do 17-20kw. Across Canada is the world's longest greenest highway, j1772 charging stations for free along the trans canada highway, which is totally impractical in anything except a tesla with a dual charger. With a portable chademo, any chademo enabled car could fully utilize these chargers. You could also have the option of running off 2 separate 240V 50a connections (like at an RV park) with the right inputs.
That's where we need community collaboration, I have strengths in mechanical, and electronic hardware, however software programming is not really my thing. I hope one day we can not only charge in the manner above, but also charge/boost another vehicle, or power your home with affordable, obtainable electronics. (what is currently in the press is certainly not obtainable by mere mortals and quite definitely not affordable)
Rule 1 - DO NOT TOUCH any plug/cable when the charger is running.
Rule 2 - Do not use when there is any kind of moisture falling on the car/charger/cables (liquid or solid).
Rule 3 - Abort the charge if the any power pin temperature reaches 50 degrees C (hot to the touch, but no risk of melting ABS plastic).
Rule 4 - Do not leave unattended. If any potential curious and uninformed people come near the car, abort the charge.
Rule 5 - DO NOT TOUCH any plug/cable when the charger is running.

NEITHER MYSELF OR THE THINGIVERSE CAN BE HELD RESPONSIBLE FOR YOUR IDIOCY. Print with support, make sure your machine is calibrated accurately. The handles will need to be rotated as they just barely fit the print bed of a reprap prusa mendel. (biggest things I ever printed). (I have a makergear unit)
The plug tip and pin holder MUST be printed in a high temperature plastic such as ABS. Do not use PLA for the tip and holder. The rest of the parts can be PLA if you prefer. My layer thickness was 0.3mm for the orange ABS sections, and 0.4mm (different nozzle) for the white PLA parts.
I have deleted older revisions to make things clear. This one is my final version, so I will be making no further updates.
After the plug is printed, the holes for the pins should be cleaned/drilled with 23/64" for the 9mm holes (pins will slide in nicely, and will not wobble). The holes for the data pins will need to be drilled for whatever thickness of neck you have for your data pins. I used 2.8mm EDM brass rod. So I drilled out the holes with a 7/64" bit and then once more about half way down with a 1/8".
The tips of the data pins are: digikey part number ED90409-ND (gold pins) are soldered onto the center of the rod using a jig.
See this blog post for instructions for the data pins:
http://erroneus.myevblog.com/2013/12/15/1-5mm-pins-for-who-knows-what/
The power pins have been much more challenging to obtain, they are 9.0mm nominal with a tolerance of +0.0 -0.1mm
I have created a way to build the pins that are good up to 50amps with a 2awg cable. (overkill for ampacity, but good for sinking heat) Details and part numbers are here: (these are the r4 pins)
http://erroneus.myevblog.com/2013/10/19/9mm-pins-for-jewelry-or-perhaps-rapid-charging-a-car/

description.text:
Quick weekend project...thought I share. Recently decided to restore my old AT-AT.
Unfortunately I lost one of the guns... seems to be quite common to loose these things :(
Originals are sold on Ebay for around 30€ (!) each!
...Naaaah! I´m not going to spend that much on a little piece of plastic!
Because I still had one left I was able measure it exactly! So, this is the closest thing you can get your hands on...aside from the original.
Tried to print it in clear PLA (originals are clear plastic) but it turned out that clear PLA is not clear after printing :(
So, I did go with grey, which looks nice.
Yes, I know...no light effect...but better than no gun. One sliced Version for better printing and one solid...if you want to go with supports. And if you want to sell a COCKPIT COVER ...which I also lost...contact me! ;)

description.text:
This is a slight improvement over the original version by @tomerna, with:

  • Larger diameter holes, the original version was binding for me and required twisting the screw in versus just pushing.

  • More rounded overall shaped and a few key fillets leading to stronger part overall.

  • Wider contact point on the outside "finger" closest to the thumb screw, original version kept breaking for me.

  • Recessed thumb screw receiver for added rigidity and tighter fit. Also so that you can actually use the included thumbscrew which is not that long.
    • *Add a 5mm, preferably Nylock nut to complete. 4th picture shows evolution of the design, with the first being @tomerna's original, second one my first prototype (not posted, still has a weak finger on one of the sides) and the final. The white ring on the final black part is due to a slight rubbing on the Panavise when installed, not a printing error. Should be fine though.

description.text: This is a wrench I designed to quickly remove standard 10mm prop nuts. Due to the different degrees of shrinkage in different printable materials (filament) I can only verify that this wrench will work when printed in PETT. If you print in other filament the wrench may be too big or too small to fit a 10mm nut. This item is also for sale on my website at http://RcPartsHangar.com. UPDATE: (12/26/15) Also prints well in PETG and HIPS but HIPS is too weak (IMO) to make a reliable tool and it will wear out quickly.
